title: For Sale/Trade:  S&W SS Model 15-2 .38 special
postcontent:
I have an immaculate, original Smith and Wesson Model 15-2 (1961-1967) in Nickel with extra Pachmyere grips. This weapon is in as near perfect condition as you can get. Fired in the neighborhood of 500 rounds.

I may take other weapons or ammo as partial trade, just shoot me a mail and let me know what you have.

Interested in: 
inexpensive tactical shotguns
 .380's
 Ammo in various calibers
 Taser C2

Here are some facts about the Model 15....

The Smith & Wesson K-38 Combat Masterpiece Revolver Model 15 is a six-shot double action revolver, with adjustable open sights, built on the medium-size "K" frame. It is chambered for the .38 Special cartridge and is fitted with a 4-inch (100 mm) barrel. Originally known as the K-38 Combat Masterpiece, it was renamed the Model 15 in 1957 when all Smith & Wesson revolvers were given numerical model numbers. It is a shorter barrel version of the Smith & Wesson Model 14 Target Masterpiece and essentially an adjustable-sight version of the seminal Smith & Wesson Model 10 ("Military and Police") revolver with target shooting features. The M&P underwent steady evolution throughout the years and S&W spun off several variations as separate models. One of these was the K-38 Target Masterpiece, which began production in 1947. The Target Masterpiece included a number of new and/or special features, including a narrow rib to provide a level sight plane, a Partridge front sight, a micrometer click rear sight, S&W’s .375” short-throw hammer, a trigger adjustment for overtravel, and improved grips. Noting the accuracy of the Target Masterpiece, a number of police departments and the FBI soon requested the same revolver with a four inch barrel and a Baughman Quick Draw front sight. The result was the K-38 Combat Masterpiece. 
In 1957 the K-38 Combat Masterpiece was renamed the Model 15 when all Smith & Wesson revolvers were given numerical model numbers. A number of production and engineering changes have been made throughout the years, some of which are noted by a dash number suffixed to the Model number. The model 15-2 was produced from 1961-1967.
 Over the years the Model 15 has been produced with several barrel lengths, with 4" being the most common. 

Production of the Model 15 was discontinued in 1999 when Smith & Wesson was purchased and reorganized.

Asking some one for a PTP or PTC is not unreasonable.  With a permit, the seller now believes that "to the best of their knowledge" that the buyer is not a felon. By you stating your disagreement with people asking for a permit tells me one of two things. 1.) You are not able to get a permit issued to you because of something on your record or 2.) you are under 21.  If it is the latter, you can go to you local PD and get a permit to purchase for long guns.  Which you need if you wanted to buy an AR or other type of assult rifle.   

Most people know the laws regarding private party sales.  I would rather see a permit than take someones word that they can legally own a gun.  

If you can find and buy from your ffl (read as gunbroker), why don't you buy it from them then.  I find it irritating that someone is only willing to pay trade in prices for things.  If I wanted trade in prices for my gun, I would trade it in.  Why is my gun worth less private sale than in a retail store?  Have you ever heard of negotiating?  I bet most of the items on these listings, the seller has an lowest amount they are willing to except.  If you don't want to pay asking price or are willing to negotiate, don't buy it and go to your fll and get it for cheaper.  

I don't care if this gets flagged.  It tells me that you read it.  I invite you to go to mnguntalk dot com and post your question on the forum and see what other people say about this subject.
